   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="original">
            <pb facs="http://lilielbe.org/media/letters/1931-12-21ThomsenHarthern.jpg"/>
            <div rend="head" style="letter">
               <p><anchor type="commentRangeStart" n="6"/>Østerbrogade 93<hi rend="super"
                     >II</hi><anchor type="commentRangeEnd" n="6"/><note type="translator"
                     source="mo" corresp="comment_6">“Østerbrogade” is the name of a street, “93” is
                     the house number and the Roman number “II” means on the second
                  floor.</note></p>
               <p><anchor type="commentRangeStart" n="7"/>København Ø. <anchor
                     type="commentRangeEnd" n="7"/><note type="translator" source="mo"
                     corresp="comment_7">“København Ø.” is the postal district.</note>
               </p>
               <p>21.12.1931</p>
            </div>
            <div rend="body">
               <p><seg n="d01">Kære <anchor type="commentRangeStart" n="1"/>Red. <anchor
                        type="commentRangeEnd" n="1"/><note type="translator" source="kej"
                        >Redaktør</note>
                     <persName key="harthernE">Harthern</persName>!</seg></p>
               <p><seg n="d02">Jeg sender <anchor type="commentRangeStart" n="2"/>dem<anchor
                        type="commentRangeEnd" n="2"/><note type="translator" source="kej"
                        >Throughout the letter, Sigurd is using de, dem, and deres as the formal
                        “you,” but they should actually be capitalized.</note> herned det jeg lovede
                     dem . .</seg>
               </p>
               <p><seg n="d03">Den lille ”gule” vil jeg sætte pris på at få returneret ved
                     lejlighed.</seg></p>
               <p><seg n="d04">Er der noget de ikke kan forstå – eller ønsker nærmere oplyst, vil
                     jeg gerne hjælpe dem med det. - Min adresse bliver fra 22/12 – 1931 til 2/1-3/1
                     1932 -</seg></p>
               <p><seg n="d05">c/o Købmand Holger Kelstrup R.a.Db.</seg> ”Borggården”</p>
               <p><seg n="d06">Kolding</seg></p>
               <p><seg n="d07">Jeg ønsker dem og deres familie en glædelig jul og et godt nytår, - -
                     og håber de kan have lidt fornøjelse af det tilsendte - - der er jo ikke noget
                     særligt. –</seg></p>

               <p><seg n="d08">Deres hengivne</seg></p>
               <signed><persName key="wegenerS">Sigurd Thomsen</persName></signed>

            </div>
            <div rend="body">
               <pb facs="http://lilielbe.org/media/letters/1921-1922ThomsenDiaryEntries.jpg"/>
               <p>
                  <anchor type="commentRangeStart" n="3"/><date when="1921-12-25"
                     >25/12</date><anchor type="commentRangeEnd" n="3"/>
                  <note type="editor" source="rjp" corresp="comment_2">Inserted loose diary
                     entries.</note>
               </p>
               <p><persName key="thomsenTC">Far</persName> satte det store billede fra <placeName
                     key="versailles">Versailles</placeName> op i dag, det var svært at faa sømmet
                  i. <persName key="wegenerE">Onkel Einar</persName> forgylder rammer og <persName
                     key="wegenerG">tante Gerda</persName> læser en roman, <anchor
                     type="commentRangeStart" n="4"/>”Paradisfuglen” af Rung<anchor
                     type="commentRangeEnd" n="4"/><note type="translator" source="kej"
                     corresp="comment_2"> Novel by Otto Rung, first published in 1919.</note>, og
                  siger at den er skrevet stakato og er for det meste beskrivelser fra det gamle
                     <placeName key="copenhagen">København</placeName> – Hjalp <persName
                     key="wegenerE">onkel Einar</persName> med at lave sine ”minustøvler”. Det
                  sneede om eftermiddagen. <persName key="thomsenTC">Fader</persName> og <persName
                     key="wegenerE">onkel Einar</persName> spillede skak, <persName key="wegenerE"
                     >Einar</persName> tabte.</p>

               <p>
                  <date when="1921-12-28">28/12.</date>
               </p>
               <p><persName key="wegenerE">Onkel Einar</persName>s fødselsdag.</p>

               <p>
                  <date when="1921-12-29">29/12.</date>
               </p>
               <p><persName key="wegenerG">Tante Gerda</persName>, <persName key="wegenerE">onkel
                     Einar</persName> og <persName key="gottliebMrs">fru Gottlieb</persName> kom mer
                  til middag med hummer. <persName key="else">Else</persName> laver mayonaise.
                     <persName key="sister">Moder</persName> var til middag en time om at spise sin
                  portion. Så var der to slags oste, 1 råden og en frisk , samt salat, mayonaise og
                     <hi rend="underline">lagkage</hi>. Der blev spillet en masse på grammaphonen og
                     <persName key="wegenerE">onkel Einar</persName> dansede en fransk Apache dans.
                  Grin m.m.</p>
               <!--AC When asking Dr. Caughie about the mother in question, she told us that "Moder" is referring to Christiane Wegener Thomsen, Einer's sister-->
               <p>
                  <date when="1922-01-03">3/1.</date>
               </p>
               <p>Blev liggende i sengen p. gr. a. Fåresyge, mægtig tyk i hovedet. Fik 1.80 Kr. af
                     <persName key="wegenerE">onkel Einar</persName>, fordi han tog <persName
                     key="else">Else</persName> med på <choice>
                     <orig>restraution</orig>
                     <reg>restauration</reg>
                  </choice>
                  <!--Sk we're not sure what to do with this part of the encoding so we just left it for now--></p>
               <p>
                  <date when="1922-01-09">9/1.</date>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <persName key="wegenerE">Onkel Einar</persName> og <persName key="wegenerG">tante
                     Gerda</persName> tog afsted med toget 10<hi rend="super">20</hi> over
                     <placeName key="gedser">Gedser</placeName></p>
            </div>
            <div rend="body">
               <pb facs="http://lilielbe.org/media/letters/1924-12UnknownUnknown.jpg"/>
               <p>
                  <anchor type="commentRangeStart" n="5"/><date when="1924-12">Dec.
                     1924</date><anchor type="commentRangeEnd" n="5"/>
                  <note type="editor" source="rjp" corresp="comment_2">Inserted loose diary
                     entry.</note>
               </p>
               <p><persName key="thomsenTC">Far</persName> fortalte os om <persName key="wegenerE"
                     >Einar</persName>, der klæder sig ud som pige. De praktiske forudsætninger
                  herfor er, hans ringe højde, velskabte skikkelse, nydelige ben og små fødder.
                  Desuden barberer han sig omhyggeligt, og ved rigelig brug af pudder og sminke kan
                  han i <placeName key="paris">Paris</placeName> ved elektrisk lys gå for en dame. –
                  Stemmen lægger han op i et sådant leje, at den kan gå for en dyb kvindestemme . –
                  Grunden til hans lyst hertil er sandsynligvis forfængelighed. – Udklædt som
                     <persName key="lili">Lili</persName> be=søgte <persName key="wegenerE"
                     >Einar</persName> os en gang medens vi boede på <placeName key="phistersStreet"
                     >Phistersvej</placeName> da <persName key="mother">hans egen mor</persName> var
                  i besøg hos os. Hun kendte ham ikke.</p>
            </div>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <div rend="head" style="letter">
               <p><anchor type="commentRangeStart" n="6"/>Østerbrogade 93<hi rend="super"
                     >II</hi><anchor type="commentRangeEnd" n="6"/><note type="translator"
                     source="mo" corresp="comment_6">“Østerbrogade” is the name of a street, “93” is
                     the house number and the Roman number “II” means on the second
                  floor.</note></p>
               <p><anchor type="commentRangeStart" n="7"/>Copenhagen East.<anchor
                     type="commentRangeEnd" n="7"/><note type="translator" source="mo"
                     corresp="comment_7">“Copenhagen East.” is the postal district.</note></p>
               <p>12.21.1931</p>
            </div>
            <div rend="body">
               <p><seg corresp="#d01">Dear <anchor type="commentRangeStart" n="1"/>Ed. <anchor
                        type="commentRangeEnd" n="1"/><note type="translator" source="kej"
                        >Editor</note> <persName key="harthernE">Harthern</persName>!</seg></p>
               <p><seg corresp="#d02">I am hereby sending you what I promised you . .</seg></p>
               <p><seg corresp="#d03">I would appreciate having the little “yellow thing” returned
                     at your convenience</seg></p>
               <p><seg corresp="#d04">If there is something you cannot understand – or wish to be
                     further informed about, I would be happy to help you with it. – My address will
                     be from 22 December – 1931 to 2 January – 3 January 1932 –</seg></p>
               <p><seg corresp="#d05">c/o Tradesman Holger Kelstrup R.a.Db. ”Borggården”</seg></p>
               <p><seg corresp="#d06">Kolding</seg></p>
               <p><seg corresp="#d07">I wish you and your family a Merry Christmas and a Happy New
                     Year, - - and hope you may have some pleasure of the item I sent - - it is
                     nothing special. –</seg></p>
               <p><seg corresp="#d08">Yours sincerely</seg></p>
               <signed><persName key="wegenerS">Sigurd Thomsen</persName></signed>

            </div>

            <div rend="body">
               <p>
                  <anchor type="commentRangeStart" n="3"/><date when="1921-12-25"
                     >25/12</date><anchor type="commentRangeEnd" n="3"/>
                  <note type="editor" source="rjp" corresp="comment_2">Inserted loose diary
                     entries.</note>
               </p>
               <p><persName key="thomsenTC">Father</persName> put up the big picture from <placeName
                     key="versailles">Versailles</placeName> today, it was hard to get the nail in.
                     <persName key="wegenerE">Uncle Einar</persName> guilds frames and <persName
                     key="wegenerG">Aunt Gerda</persName> reads a novel, <anchor
                     type="commentRangeStart" n="2"/>”The Paradise Bird” by Rung<anchor
                     type="commentRangeEnd" n="2"/><note type="translator" source="kej"
                     corresp="comment_2"> Novel by Otto Rung, first published in 1919.</note>, and
                  says that it is written staccato and is for the most part descriptions from old
                     <placeName key="copenhagen">Copenhagen</placeName> -– Helped <persName
                     key="wegenerE">Uncle Einar</persName> make his ”low heels”. It snowed in the
                  afternoon. <persName key="thomsenTC">Father</persName> and <persName
                     key="wegenerE">Uncle Einar</persName> played chess, <persName key="wegenerE"
                     >Einar</persName> lost.</p>
               <p>
                  <date when="1921-12-28">28/12.</date>
               </p>
               <p><persName key="wegenerE">Uncle Einar</persName>’s birthday.</p>
               <p>
                  <date when="1921-12-29">29/12.</date>
               </p>
               <p><persName key="wegenerG">Aunt Gerda</persName>, <persName key="wegenerE">Uncle
                     Einar</persName> and <persName key="gottliebMrs">Mrs. Gottlieb</persName> are
                  coming to dinner with lobster. <persName key="else">Else</persName> is making
                  mayonnaise. <persName key="sister">Mother</persName> took an hour to eat her
                  portion at dinner. Then there were two kinds of cheese, one moldy and one fresh,
                  as well as salad, mayonnaise, and <hi rend="underline">birthday cake</hi>. There
                  was a lot played on the grammaphone and <persName key="wegenerE">Uncle
                     Einar</persName> danced a French Apache dance. Laughter etc. </p>
               <p>
                  <date when="1922-01-03">3/1.</date>
               </p>
               <p>Stayed in bed because of mumps, mighty swollen head. Received 1.80 kroner from
                     <persName key="wegenerE">Uncle Einar</persName> because he took <persName
                     key="else">Else</persName> to a restaurant. </p>
               <p>
                  <date when="1922-01-09">9/1.</date>
               </p>
               <p><persName key="wegenerE">Uncle Einar</persName> and <persName key="wegenerG">Aunt
                     Gerda</persName> left on the train at 10<hi rend="super">20</hi> via <placeName
                     key="gedser">Gedser</placeName>
               </p>
            </div>
            <div rend="body">
               <p>
                  <anchor type="commentRangeStart" n="5"/><date when="1924-12">Dec.
                     1924</date><anchor type="commentRangeEnd" n="5"/>
                  <note type="editor" source="rjp" corresp="comment_2">Inserted loose diary
                     entry.</note>
               </p>
               <p><persName key="thomsenTC">Father</persName> told us about <persName key="wegenerE"
                     >Einar</persName>, who dresses like a girl. The convenient conditions for this
                  are his small stature, well-formed figure, beautiful legs and small feet. Moreover
                  he shaves carefully and with ample use of powder and makeup he can in <placeName
                     key="paris">Paris</placeName> by electric light pass for a lady. -– He raises
                  his voice up at such a pitch that it can pass for a deep woman’s voice. -– The
                  reason for his desire for this is probably vanity. -– Dressed as <persName
                     key="lili">Lili</persName>
                  <persName key="wegenerE"> Einar</persName> visited us once when we lived on
                     <placeName key="phistersStreet">Phisters Street</placeName> when <persName
                     key="mother">his own mother</persName> was visiting us. She did not recognize
                  him.</p>
               <!--end of 19241200-->
            </div>
         </div>
      </body>
